Course Description
Functional analysis is the study of (potentially innite-dimensional) vector spaces and linear
functions on them. We will begin by discussing the denition of Banach (normed) and Hilbert (inner
product) spaces, then get into the meat of linear operators boundedness, extensions, etc. Functional
vector spaces are pretty key examples throughout this and so we will spend time constructing these
examples. The goal will be to build up to spectral theory, a subeld of functional analysis that concerns
with dening a more abstract form of "eigenvalue" for general vector spaces. Spectral theory proves
ubiquitous because we can learn a lot about dierential operators and more on function spaces by
studying their spectrum.

Class Schedule
Week 1, 10/27 - 11/3: Preliminaries: Metric Spaces
Be able to prove:
Whether a bilinear map is a metric
Other formulations of the triangle inequality
Whether simple metric spaces are separable
The equivalence between closure and limits of convergent sequences
The equivalence between topological continuous functions and sequential continuous functions
Basic convergence properties about Cauchy and convergent sequences
Be able to state, understand, and apply:
Denition of a metric and know some standard metrics
Holder inequality for sums (and the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality for sums)
Minkowski inequality for sums
Denitions and basic properties of open/closed sets and their variants (interior, closure)
Denition of continuity
Denition of dense/separable sets
Denitions and basic properties of Cauchy and convergent sequences
Denition of completeness
